@dataclass
class Dataset:
    images: pd .DataFrame
    labels: pd.DataFrame

def read_dataset(image_path, label_path):
    images = pd.read_csv(image_path, header=None)
    images = images.astype('uint8')
    labels = pd.read_csv(label_path, header=None)
    labels = labels.astype('uint8')
    
    return Dataset(images=images, labels=labels)

def show_image(image: pd.Series, description='just an image from the dataset', ax=None):
    coeff = 255 // np.max(image.values)
    image = (image * coeff)
    image = image.astype('int8')
    r_image = image.values.reshape(32, 32)
    img = Image.fromarray(r_image.T, 'L')
    if ax is None:
        plt.figure()
        plt.imshow(img, cmap='gray', vmin=0, vmax=255)
        print(description)
        plt.show()
        print()
        return
    ax.set_title(description)
    ax.imshow(img, cmap='gray', vmin=0, vmax=255)

def show_sample_images(df : Dataset):
    total_classes = df.labels[0].unique()
    ncols = 7
    nrows = max((len(total_classes) + ncols - 1) // ncols, 2)
    i, j = ncols, 0
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(ncols=ncols, nrows=nrows, figsize=(10*nrows, 27))
    for label in total_classes:
        i -= 1
        img_idx = list(df.labels[0][df.labels[0] == label].index)
        sample_idx = random.choice(img_idx)
        img = df.images.loc[sample_idx]
        desc = f"sample image with label {label}"
        show_image(image=img, description=desc, ax=ax[j][i])
        if i == 0:
            j += 1
            i = ncols
    plt.show()

def check_frequencies(**dfs):
    values_freq = dict()
    total_classes = set()
    total_data_count = 0
    for title, df in dfs.items():
        _values_freq = df.labels[0].value_counts().sort_index()
        plt.bar(_values_freq.index, _values_freq.values, label=title)
        values_freq[title] = _values_freq
        
        data_count = len(df.labels)
        labels = set(df.labels[0].unique())
        total_data_count += data_count
        total_classes = total_classes.union(labels)
        print(f"{title}:")
        print(f"- total data:    {data_count}")
        print(f"- total classes: {len(labels)}")
        print()
    
    print("summary report:")
    print(f"- total data:    {total_data_count}")
    print(f"- total classes: {len(total_classes)}")
    print(f"- classes:       {total_classes}")
    
    
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()
    return pd.DataFrame(values_freq).T

def reduce_by_label(df: Dataset, v_labels):
    valid_idx = []
    for vl in v_labels:
        valid_idx.extend(list(df.labels[0][df.labels[0] == vl].index))
    df.labels = df.labels.iloc[valid_idx]
    df.images = df.images.iloc[valid_idx]

06. Rescale pixel's value¶

  • Scaling is used to set the pixels values in the range of 0 to 1; why?
    • Neural Networks process inputs using small weight values, and inputs with large integer values can disrupt or even slow down the learning process.

01. DataLoader¶

In [ ]:
class Dataloader:
    """
    This class prepares the dataset for the neural network.
    """
    
    def __init__(
        self,
        data: pd.DataFrame,
        labels: pd.DataFrame,
        n_classes: int,
        batch_size: int = None, 
        shuffle: bool = False
        ):
        """
        This is the constructor. It gets dataset information and initializes the
        Dataloader class fields.
            Parameters:
                data: features your dataset in pandas.Dataframe format.
                labels: labels of your dataset in pandas.Dataframe format.
                n_classes: number of classes you have in your dataset.
                batch_size: the number of samples that will be propagated through the network.
                shuffle: boolean value indicating whether the dataset should be shuffled
        """

        assert len(data)==len(labels)
        self.__n_classes = n_classes
        self.__batch_size = batch_size
        self.__shuffle = shuffle
        self.__data = data
        self.__onehot_labels = self.__onehot(labels, self.__n_classes)
    
    @staticmethod
    def __onehot(labels, n_classes):
        """
        This private method gets labels and provides one_hot vectors of labels.
        For categorical variables where no such ordinal relationship exists,
        the integer encoding is not enough.
        In this case, a one-hot encoding can be applied to the integer representation.
        This is where the integer encoded variable is removed, and a new binary variable is
        added for each unique integer value.
        example:
            red,    green,    blue
            1,      0,        0
            0,      1,        0
            0,      0,        1
                Parameters:
                        labels: labels of your dataset in pandas.Dataframe format.
                        n_classes: number of classes you have in your dataset.

                Returns:
                    onehot_vectors: onehot vectors of the labels
        """
        onehot_vectors = pd.DataFrame(OneHotEncoder().fit_transform(labels).toarray(),index=labels.index)
        return onehot_vectors
    
    def __shuffle_dataset(self):
        """
        This private method shuffles your dataset.
        It uses data and onehot_labels to shuffle them
        symmetrical.
        """
        perm = np.random.permutation(self.__data.shape[0])
        self.__data = self.__data.iloc[perm]
        self.__onehot_labels = self.__onehot_labels.iloc[perm]
    
    def __iter__(self):
        """
        The __iter__() function returns an iterator for the
        given object (array, set, tuple, etc., or custom objects).
        This will return your dataset in the batch_size given. This should
        be used to provide data for the neural network.
        """
        
        if self.__shuffle:
            self.__shuffle_dataset()
            
        if self.__batch_size is None:
            yield np.matrix(self.__data), np.matrix(self.__onehot_labels)
            return
            
        for idx in range(0, len(self.__data), self.__batch_size):
            yield (np.matrix(self.__data[idx:idx+self.__batch_size]), 
                   np.matrix(self.__onehot_labels[idx:idx+self.__batch_size]))

02. Activation Functions¶

01. Identical¶

This activation function just return the value it gets.

In [ ]:
class Identical:
    """
    This is the Identical activation function. This activation function just
    return the value it gets.
    """
    
    def __init__(self): pass

    @staticmethod
    def __val(matrix: np.matrix):
        """
        This private method gets a matrix and uses the activity function on that.
        As this is an identical activity function, it just
        returns matrix of the input.

            Parameters:
                matrix: np.matrix of values
            Returns:
                identical_value: np.matrix of input with float datatypes
        """

        identical_value = np.matrix(matrix, dtype=float)
        return identical_value

    @staticmethod
    def derivative(matrix):
        """
        This method returns the derivation of the input.
        As the derivation of x is one, this method returns
        a matrix of one with the shape of the input matrix.

            Parameters:
                matrix: np.matrix of values
            Returns:
                identical_derivative: np.matrix of ones with matrix shape
        """
        
        identical_derivative = np.matrix(np.full(np.shape(matrix), 1.))
        return identical_derivative
    
    def __call__(self, matrix):
        """
        __call__ is a special function in Python that, when implemented inside a class,
        gives its instances (objects) the ability to behave like a function.
        Here we return the _value method output.

            Parameters:
                matrix: np.matrix of values
            Returns:
                __val(matrix): __val return value for the input matrix
        """
        
        return self.__val(matrix)

02. Relu¶

Rectified Linear Activation Function(ReLU) is a piecewise linear function that will output the input directly if it is positive, otherwise, it will output zero.

In [ ]:
class Relu:
    """
    This is the Relu activation function.
    The rectified linear activation function or ReLU for short
    is a piecewise linear function that will output the input directly
    if it is positive, otherwise, it will output zero.
    """
    
    def __init__(self): pass
    
    @staticmethod
    def __val(matrix):
        """
        This private method gets a matrix and uses the activity function on that.
        It will set 0 in the matrix if the value is less than 0 else, it returns the value itself.

            Parameters:
                matrix: np.matrix of values
            Returns:
                relu_value: np.matrix of relu activation function result
        """
        
        relu_value = np.maximum(0, matrix)
        return relu_value

    @staticmethod
    def derivative(matrix):
        """
        Returns the derivation value of relu function on input matrix.

            Parameters:
                matrix: np.matrix of values
            Returns:
                relu_derivative: np.matrix of relu activation function derivation result
        """
        
        relu_derivative = np.matrix(np.full(np.shape(matrix), np.where(matrix >= 0, 1, 0)))
        return relu_derivative
    
    def __call__(self, matrix):
        """
        __call__ is a special function in Python that, when implemented inside a class,
        gives its instances (objects) the ability to behave like a function.
        Here we return the _relu method output.

            Parameters:
                matrix: np.matrix of values
            Returns:
                __relu(matrix): __relu return value for the input matrix
        """
        
        return self.__val(matrix)

03. LeakyRelu¶

Leaky Rectified Linear Unit(Leaky ReLU) is a type of activation function based on a ReLU, but it has a small slope for negative values instead of a flat slope.

In [ ]:
class LeakyRelu:
    """
    This is the Leaky Relu activation function.
    Leaky Rectified Linear Unit, or Leaky ReLU,
    is a type of activation function based on a ReLU,
    but it has a small slope for negative values instead
    of a flat slope.
    """
    
    def __init__(self, negative_slope=0.01):
        self.negative_slope = negative_slope
    
    def __val(self, matrix):
        """
        This private method gets a matrix and uses the activity function on that.
        It will set negative_slope*value in the matrix if the value is less than 0, else it
        returns the value itself.

            Parameters:
                matrix: np.matrix of values
            Returns:
                relu_value: np.matrix of relu activation function result
        """
        
        temp = np.matrix(matrix, dtype=float)
        leaky_relu_value = np.where(temp < 0, temp * self.negative_slope, temp)
        return leaky_relu_value

    def derivative(self, matrix):
        """
        Returns the derivation value of leaky relu function on input matrix.

            Parameters:
                matrix: np.matrix of values
            Returns:
                leaky_relu_derivative: np.matrix of leaky relu activation function derivation result
        """
        
        leaky_relu_derivative = np.matrix(np.full(np.shape(matrix), np.where(matrix >= 0, 1, self.negative_slope)))
        return leaky_relu_derivative
    
    def __call__(self, matrix):
        """
        __call__ is a special function in Python that, when implemented inside a class,
        gives its instances (objects) the ability to behave like a function.
        Here we return the _val method output.

            Parameters:
                matrix: np.matrix of values
            Returns:
                __val(matrix): __val return value for the input matrix
        """
        
        return self.__val(matrix)

04. Sigmoid¶

It is a mathematical function having a characteristic "S"-shaped curve or sigmoid curve. It returns $S(x)= \frac{1}{1+\exp^{-x}}$

In [ ]:
class Sigmoid:
    """
    A sigmoid function is a mathematical function having a
    characteristic "S"-shaped curve or sigmoid curve.
    It returns S(x)=1/(1+e^-x)
    """
    
    def __init__(self): pass

    @staticmethod
    def __val(matrix):
        """
        Returns 1/(1+e^-x) of values

            Parameters:
                matrix: np.matrix of values
            Returns:
                sigmoid_value: np.matrix of relu activation function result
        """
        temp = np.matrix(matrix, dtype=float)
        sigmoid_value = 1 / (1 + np.exp(-temp))
        return sigmoid_value

    def derivative(self, matrix):
        """
        Returns the derivation value of sigmoid function on input matrix.

            Parameters:
                matrix: np.matrix of values
            Returns:
                sigmoid_derivative: np.matrix of sigmoid activation function derivation result
        """
        sig = self.__val(matrix)
        sigmoid_derivative = np.multiply(sig, (1 - sig))
        return sigmoid_derivative
    
    def __call__(self, matrix):
        """
        __call__ is a special function in Python that, when implemented inside a class,
        gives its instances (objects) the ability to behave like a function.
        Here we return the _val method output.

            Parameters:
                matrix: np.matrix of values
            Returns:
                __val(matrix): __val return value for the input matrix
        """
        return self.__val(matrix)

05. Softmax¶

It is a generalization of the logistic function to multiple dimensions. It is used in multinomial logistic regression and is often used as the last activation function of a neural network to normalize the output of a network to a probability distribution over predicted output classes, based on Luce's choice axiom. Softmax returns ${\frac{e^{x_i}}{\sum{e^{x_i}}}}$.

Attention: we use stable softmax to avoid this issue.

In [ ]:
def soft_max_util(row):
    """helping to applying stable softmax"""
    nmd = np.exp(row - np.max(row))
    denominator = np.sum(nmd)
    ssm = nmd / denominator
    return ssm


class Softmax:
    """
    The softmax function, also known as soft argmax  or normalized
    exponential function is a generalization of the logistic
    function to multiple dimensions. It is used in multinomial logistic
    regression and is often used as the last activation function of a neural
    network to normalize the output of a network to a probability distribution
    over predicted output classes, based on Luce's choice axiom.
    Softmax return (e^x_i / (Σe^x_j for j = 1, ..., J))
    """
        
    def __init__(self): pass

    @staticmethod
    def __val(matrix):
        """
        This private method gets a matrix and uses the softmax on that.
        Softmax return (e^x_i / (Σe^x_j for j = 1, ..., J))

            Parameters:
                matrix: np.matrix of values
            Returns:
                relu_value: np.matrix of relu activation function result
        """
        e = np.exp(matrix - np.max(matrix))
        return e / e.sum(axis=1).reshape([matrix.shape[0], 1])
        # return np.apply_along_axis(soft_max_util, 1, matrix)
    
    def __call__(self, matrix):
        """
        __call__ is a special function in Python that, when implemented inside a class,
        gives its instances (objects) the ability to behave like a function.
        Here we return the _val method output.

            Parameters:
                matrix: np.matrix of values
            Returns:
                __val(matrix): __val return value for the input matrix
        """
        
        return self.__val(matrix)

class Tanh:
    
    def __init__(self): pass

    @staticmethod
    def __val(matrix):
        """
        This private method gets a matrix and uses the activity function on that.
        It performs Tanh on the values.

            Parameters:
                matrix: np.matrix of values
            Returns:
                tanh_value: np.matrix of Tanh activation function result
        """
        
        temp = np.matrix(matrix, dtype=float)
        tanh_value = np.tanh(temp)
        return tanh_value

    def derivative(self, matrix):
        """
        Returns the derivation value of Tanh function on input matrix.

            Parameters:
                matrix: np.matrix of values
            Returns:
                sigmoid_derivative: np.matrix of Tanh activation function derivation result
        """
        
        tanh_derivative = 1 - np.power(self.__val(matrix), 2)
        return tanh_derivative
    
    def __call__(self, matrix):
        """
        __call__ is a special function in Python that, when implemented inside a class,
        gives its instances (objects) the ability to behave like a function.
        Here we return the _val method output.

            Parameters:
                matrix: np.matrix of values
            Returns:
                __val(matrix): __val return value for the input matrix
        """
        
        return self.__val(matrix)

03. Loss Function¶

We use cross entropy with softmax as loss function.

Cross-entropy is a measure of the difference between two probability distributions for a given random variable or set of events. You might recall that information quantifies the number of bits required to encode and transmit an event.

In [ ]:
class CrossEntropy:
    """
    Cross-entropy is a measure of the difference between two probability
    distributions for a given random variable or set of events. You might
    recall that information quantifies the number of bits required to encode
    and transmit an event.
    """

    def __init__(self): 
        self.softmax = Softmax()

    def __val(self, true_val, expected_val):
        """
        L(y^, y) = - Σ (y^(k)log (y^)^(k)) for k in K
        Parameters:
            true_val: calculated values (generated by neural network)
            expected_val: real values in dataset
        Returns:
            cross_entropy_value: cross entropy of inputs
        """

        assert np.shape(true_val) == np.shape(expected_val)

        generated = np.log(self.softmax(true_val))
        cross_entropy_value =  np.sum(-np.multiply(expected_val, generated), axis=1)

        return cross_entropy_value

    def derivative(self, true_val, expected_val):
        """
        Returns derivation of cross entropy.
            Parameters:
                true_val: calculated values (generated by neural network)
                expected_val: real values in dataset
            Returns:
                cross_entropy_derivative: cross entropy derivation of inputs
        """

        assert np.shape(true_val)==np.shape(expected_val)

        generated = self.softmax(true_val)
        cross_entropy_derivative = generated - expected_val

        return cross_entropy_derivative

    def __call__(self, true_val, expected_val):
        """
        __call__ is a special function in Python that, when implemented inside a class,
        gives its instances (objects) the ability to behave like a function.
        Here we return the _val method output.

            Parameters:
                true_val: calculated values (generated by neural network)
                expected_val: real values in dataset
            Returns:
                __val(matrix): __val return value for the input matrix
        """

        return self.__val(true_val, expected_val)

class Layer:
    """
    The layer class is used to define neural network layers.
    It stores all needed information for each layer, such as neurons count,
    weight matrix, bias, the output after applying the activation function, etc.
    """

    DEFAULT_LOW = 0
    DEFAULT_HIGH = 0.05 
    DEFAULT_MEAN = 0.0
    DEFAULT_VAR = 1.0
  
    def __init__(self, input_size, output_size, activation=Identical(), initial_weight='uniform', 
                 **initializing_parameters):
        """
        Parameters:
            input_size: the size of the input of this layer.
            output_size: the size of the output after this layer.
            activation: the activation function. It can be initialized to either of the previously defined activation classes.
                               default is an Identical activation function.
            initial_weight: either normal or uniform. It defines the method for weight initialization.
        """
        
        assert type(initial_weight)==str, 'Undefined activation function!'
        
        self.__weight_initializer_dict = {'uniform':self.__uniform_weight, 'normal':self.__normal_weight, 'zero': self.__zero_weight}
        
        assert initial_weight in self.__weight_initializer_dict, 'Undefined weight initialization function!'


        self.__n_neurons = output_size
        weight_initializer = self.__weight_initializer_dict[initial_weight]
        self.__weight = weight_initializer(input_size, self.__n_neurons, **initializing_parameters)
        self.__bias = weight_initializer(1, self.__n_neurons, **initializing_parameters)
        self.__activation = activation
        
        self.__last_input = None
        self.__last_activation_input = None
        self.__last_activation_output = None
        self.__last_activation_derivative = None
        
    def forward(self, layer_input):
        """
        It calculates the output of this layer for the layer_input argument.
        This method also stores __last_input, __last_activation_input, and __last_activation_derivative
        for future use in backpropagation.
        Parameters:
            layer_input: 2d np.matrix representing the input matrix of this layer.
        Returns:
            Final output of this layer after applying the activation function.
        """
        
        assert np.ndim(layer_input) == 2
        assert np.size(self.__weight, 0) == np.size(layer_input, 1)
        
        # storing the input for back-propagation
        self.__last_input = np.matrix(layer_input, dtype=float)
        
        # calculating input and output of activation and output's derivation
        self.__last_activation_input = np.add(np.dot(self.__last_input, self.__weight), self.__bias)
        self.__last_activation_output = self.__activation(self.__last_activation_input)
        self.__last_activation_derivative = self.__activation.derivative(self.__last_activation_input)     
           
        return self.__last_activation_output
    
    def update_weights(self, backprop_tensor, lr):
        """
        It updates Layer weights according to the backpropagation matrix and learning rate.
        This method updates bias values as well.
        Parameters:
            backprop_tensor: 2d np.matrix passed from the next layer containing gradient values.
            lr: learning rate
        Returns:
            backprop_tensor to be used by the previous layer.
        """
        
        assert np.ndim(backprop_tensor)==2
        assert np.size(backprop_tensor,0) == np.size(self.__last_activation_derivative,0)
        assert np.size(backprop_tensor,1) == self.__n_neurons
        
        ones = np.matrix(np.ones((1, np.size(backprop_tensor,axis=0))))
        dy = np.multiply(backprop_tensor, self.__last_activation_derivative)
        db = np.matmul(ones, dy)
        dw = np.matmul(self.__last_input.T, dy)
        
        backprop_tensor = np.matmul(dy, self.__weight.T)

        self.__weight -= lr * dw
        self.__bias -= lr * db
        
        return backprop_tensor

    def __uniform_weight(self, dim1, dim2, **initializing_parameters):
        """
        Initializes weights as a uniform distribution between low and high values.
        It uses default low and high values unless low or high are passed in initializing_parameters.
        Parameters:
            dim1: the size of the first dimension of weights.
            dim2: the size of the second dimension of weights.
            initializing_parameters: other initializing parameters; it can include custom low or high values.
        Returns:
            np.matrix with size (dim1, dim2) initialized using uniformly distributed values.
        """
        
        low = self.DEFAULT_LOW
        high = self.DEFAULT_HIGH
        if 'low' in initializing_parameters.keys(): low = initializing_parameters['low']
        if 'high' in initializing_parameters.keys(): high = initializing_parameters['high']
        weights = np.matrix(np.random.uniform(low=low, high=high, size=(dim1, dim2)))
        
        return weights

    def __normal_weight(self, dim1, dim2, **initializing_parameters):
        """
        Initializes weights as a normal distribution with mean and var values.
        It uses default mean and variance values unless mean or var are passed in initializing_parameters.
        Parameters:
            dim1: the size of the first dimension of weights.
            dim2: the size of the second dimension of weights.
            initializing_parameters: other initializing parameters; it can include custom mean or var values.
        Returns:
            np.matrix with size (dim1, dim2) initialized using normally distributed values.
        """ 
        
        mean = self.DEFAULT_MEAN
        var = self.DEFAULT_VAR
        if 'mean' in initializing_parameters.keys(): mean = initializing_parameters['mean']
        if 'var' in initializing_parameters.keys(): var = initializing_parameters['var']
        weights = np.matrix(np.random.normal(loc = mean, scale = np.sqrt(var), size=(dim1, dim2)))
        
        return weights
    
    def __zero_weight(self, dim1, dim2, **initializing_parameters):
        """Initializes weights to zero"""
        return np.zeros(shape=(dim1, dim2))
    
    @property
    def n_neurons(self): 
        return self.__n_neurons
    
    @property
    def weight(self): 
        return self.__weight
    
    @property
    def bias(self): 
        return self.__bias
    
    @property
    def activation(self): 
        return self.__activation

class FeedForwardNeuralNetwork:
    """
    This class is used in order to implement custom feed-forward neural networks.
    The FeedForwardNN class stores a list of layers that determines all network layers.
    It also consists of the learning rate and loss function.
    """
    def __init__(self, input_shape: int):
        """
        Parameters:
            input_shape: the size of the first input to our neural network.
        """
        
        self.__input_shape: int = input_shape
        self.__output_shape: int = None
        
        self.__layers_list: list[Layer] = []
        
        self.__lr: int = None
        self.__loss = None

        
    def add_layer(self, n_neurons, activation=Relu(), initial_weight='uniform', **initializing_parameters):
        """
         This method adds a new custom layer to the layers_list.
         Parameters:
             n_neurons: number of neurons in this layer
             activation: the activation function of this layer, default is Relu
             initial_weight: either a uniform or normal, default is uniform
             initializing_parameters: other initializing parameters such as low, high, mean, var, etc
        """
         
        assert type(n_neurons)==int, "Invalid number of neurons for the layer!"
        assert n_neurons>0, "Invalid number of neurons for the layer!"
        
        n_prev_neurons = self.__input_shape if len(self.__layers_list) == 0 else self.__layers_list[-1].n_neurons
        new_layer = Layer(n_prev_neurons, n_neurons, activation, initial_weight, **initializing_parameters)
        self.__layers_list.append(new_layer)
        self.__output_shape = self.__layers_list[-1].n_neurons 
      
    
    def set_training_param(self, loss=CrossEntropy(), lr=1e-3):
        """
        This method is used to set training parameters.
        Parameters:
            loss: loss function, default is CrossEntropy
            lr: learning rate, default is 1e-3
        """
        
        assert self.__layers_list, "Uncompleted model!"
        self.__loss = loss
        self.__lr = lr
    
    
    def forward(self, network_input):
        """
        This method calculates the output of the complete neural network for a passed input.
        Parameters:
            network_input: input of the neural network
        Returns:
            network_output: output of the neural network after forwarding the network_input
        """
        
        assert self.__output_shape is not None, "Model is not compiled!"
        
        network_output = network_input
        for layer in self.__layers_list:
            network_output = layer.forward(network_output)
        return network_output
    
    
    def fit(self, epochs, train_loader: Dataloader, test_loader: Dataloader = None, print_results=True):
        """
        This method trains the neural network using specified parameters.
        It runs the __train private method epoch times and fills the log dictionary.
        Parameters:
            epochs: number of epochs to run
            train_loader: DataLoader for train data
            test_loader: DataLoader for test data
            print_results: whether to print the results
        Returns:
            log: complete log of the training process as a dictionary consisting of
            train_accuracy, train_loss, test_accuracy, test_loss
        """
        
        assert self.__output_shape is not None, "Model is not compiled!"
        assert (self.__lr is not None) and (self.__loss is not None), "Training parameters are not set!"

        log = {"train_accuracy":[], "train_loss":[], "test_accuracy":[], "test_loss":[]}
        
        for epoch in range(1, epochs+1):
            
            if print_results: 
                res = f"Epoch #{epoch}\n"
                
            average_accuracy, average_loss = self.__train(train_loader)
            log['train_accuracy'].append(average_accuracy)
            log['train_loss'].append(average_loss)
            if print_results:
                res += f'\tTrain: Average Accuracy: {average_accuracy:.1f}%\tAverage Loss: {average_loss:.1f}\n'
            
            if test_loader is not None:
                average_accuracy, average_loss = self.__test(test_loader)
                log['test_accuracy'].append(average_accuracy)
                log['test_loss'].append(average_loss)
                if print_results:
                    res += f'\tTest:  Average Accuracy: {average_accuracy:.1f}%\tAverage Loss: {average_loss:.1f}'
                    print(res)
                    
        return log
    
    
    def __train(self, train_loader: Dataloader):
        """
        Trains the neural network for one epoch.
        Parameters:
            train_loader: A DataLoader consisting of train data
        Returns:
            batch_accuracy, batch_loss: mean of all batch_accuracies, batch_losses
        """
        
        bach_accuracies, batch_losses = [], []
        for x_train, y_train in train_loader:
            batch_accuracy, batch_loss = self.__train_on_batch(x_train, y_train)
            bach_accuracies.append(batch_accuracy)
            batch_losses.append(batch_loss)
        return np.mean(bach_accuracies), np.mean(batch_losses)
    
    
    def __test(self, test_loader: Dataloader):
        """
        Test the neural network using a test_loader.
        Parameters:
            test_loader: A DataLoader of test data
        Returns:
            batch_accuracy, batch_loss: mean of all batch_accuracies, batch_losses
        """
        
        bach_accuracies, batch_losses = [], []
        for x_test, y_test in test_loader:
            batch_accuracy, batch_loss = self.__test_on_batch(x_test, y_test)
            bach_accuracies.append(batch_accuracy)
            batch_losses.append(batch_loss)
        return np.mean(bach_accuracies), np.mean(batch_losses)

    
    def __train_on_batch(self, x_batch, y_batch):
        """
        Trains the neural network for one batch of train data.
        Parameters:
            x_batch: one batch data
            y_batch: labels for one batch
        Returns:
            (batch_accuracy, batch_average_loss)
        """
        
        nn_result = self.forward(x_batch)

        batch_accuracy = self.__compute_accuracy(nn_result, y_batch)
        batch_average_loss = np.mean(self.__loss(nn_result, y_batch))
        
        self.__update_weights(nn_result, y_batch)
        
        return batch_accuracy, batch_average_loss
        
        
    def __test_on_batch(self, x_batch, y_batch):
        """
        Tests the neural network for one batch of test data.
        Parameters:
            x_batch: one batch data
            y_batch: labels for one batch
        Returns:
            (batch_accuracy, batch_average_loss)
        """  
        
        nn_result = self.forward(x_batch)

        batch_accuracy = self.__compute_accuracy(nn_result, y_batch)
        batch_average_loss = np.mean(self.__loss(nn_result, y_batch))
        
        return batch_accuracy, batch_average_loss
            
        
    @staticmethod
    def __get_labels(outputs):
        """
        Parameters:
            outputs: output of the neural network
        Returns:
            labels: labels generated from the outputs of the neural network
        """
        
        labels = np.argmax(outputs, 1)
        return labels
    
    
    def __compute_accuracy(self, output, expected_output):
        """
        Computes accuracy by comparing output and expected_output.
        Parameters:
            output: actual output of the neural network
            expected_output: expected output
        Returns:
            accuracy
        """
        
        labels = self.__get_labels(output)
        expected_labels = self.__get_labels(expected_output)
        accuracy = 100 * accuracy_score(expected_labels, labels)
        return accuracy
    
    
    def __update_weights(self, output, y_train):
        """
        Updates weights of all layers according to neural network output and labels.
        Parameters:
            output: output of the neural network
            y_train: y labels for one batch of train data
        Returns:
            None
        """
        
        back_propagation_tensor = self.__loss.derivative(output, y_train)
        for layer in reversed(self.__layers_list):
            back_propagation_tensor = layer.update_weights(back_propagation_tensor, self.__lr)
        return

def plot_logs(logs : dict):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(13, 5))
    ax[0].set_title('Accuracy')
    ax[0].set_ylabel('Accuracy (%)')
    ax[0].set_xlabel('Epoch')
    ax[0].plot(logs['train_accuracy'], label='Train')
    ax[0].plot(logs['test_accuracy'], label='Test')
    ax[0].legend()
    
    ax[1].set_title('Loss')
    ax[1].set_ylabel('Loss')
    ax[1].set_xlabel('Epoch')
    ax[1].plot(logs['train_loss'], label='Train')
    ax[1].plot(logs['test_loss'], label='Test')
    ax[1].legend()
    
    plt.show()

04. Parameter's effect¶

In [ ]:
def test_network_config(l_r=LEARNING_RATE, active=Relu, init_weight='uniform', epoch=EPOCHS, out=True, plot=True, ret_acc=False, loader=(TRAIN_LOADER,TEST_LOADER)):
    network = FeedForwardNeuralNetwork(INPUT_SHAPE)

    network.add_layer(n_neurons=50, activation=active(), initial_weight=init_weight)
    network.add_layer(n_neurons=90, activation=active(), initial_weight=init_weight)
    network.add_layer(n_neurons=N_CLASSES, activation=Identical(), initial_weight=init_weight)
    network.set_training_param(loss=CrossEntropy(), lr=l_r)

    log = network.fit(epochs=epoch, train_loader=loader[0], test_loader=loader[1], print_results=out)
    if plot:
        plot_logs(log)
    if ret_acc:
        return {'train': log['train_accuracy'][-1] , 'test': log['test_accuracy'][-1]}

01. Weights initialization¶

What if we used zero values as layers' weight initial value?

In this case:

  • the derivatives will remain the same
  • neural network can't learn features
  • this leads to convergence interruption, because gradient decent can't update weights
    • due to backprop_tensor = np.matmul(dy, self.__weight.T), backprop_tensor would became zero
    • so, GD can't help optimizing model
  • issue exist if we use same constant value to initialization and all nodes, would send the same signal ($InputSum * Const$) [called symmetric problem]
  • no matter what was the input, if all weights are the same, all units in hidden layer will be the same too.
  • so, we use random initialization to Break symmetry

02. Leaning rate¶

We will consider three cases here:

  • lower learning rate
    • used $\frac{1}{10}$ of the default learning rete ($0.005 * 0.01 = 0.0005$)
    • it takes longer for the model to find the optimal values
    • we need more epoch to reach optimum
  • higher learning rate
    • used $15$ of the default learning rete ($0.005 * 15 = 0.075$)
    • model diverged and couldn't find the optimal values
    • if it's not as high as causing divergence, in could speed up fitting process (and using lower epoch)
  • optimum learning rate
    • we discoverd optimum learning rate for our network is 0.0046

03. optimum learning rate¶

In [ ]:
best_acc, best_lr = 0, 0
st, end = LEARNING_RATE * 0.2, LEARNING_RATE * 2
steps = 10
coeff = (end - st) / steps
for c in range(steps):
    _lr = st + c*coeff
    acc = test_network_config(l_r=_lr, ret_acc=True, out=False, plot=False)
    if acc['test'] > best_acc:
        best_acc = acc['test']
        best_lr = _lr
print(f"The best learning rete for this network structure is: {best_lr} with accuracy: {best_acc:.1f}%")

The best learning rete for this network structure is: 0.0046 with accuracy: 78.5%
In [ ]:
OPTIMUM_LEARNING_RATE = best_lr

03. Activation function¶

We would try following cases:

  • Sigmoid
    • normalizes the values in $range=(0, 1)$ and when argument is a large positive or negative value, it' will get close to $0$
    • decreased model's convergence speed
  • Hyperbolic Tangent
    • normalizes the values in $range=(-1, 1)$ and also, it's a zero centered function
    • overfitted model extremely
  • Leaky ReLU
    • has the best performance
    • converged faster

Sigmoid and tanh activation functions are not commonly used in deep learning anymore due to several reasons:

  • Saturation: Both sigmoid and tanh activation functions saturate at their extremes (0 or 1 for sigmoid, -1 or 1 for tanh), the gradients at these extremes become very small:
    • leading to slow or even non-existent weight updates during backpropagation.
  • Vanishing gradients: This saturation can also result in the vanishing gradients problem, where the gradients become so small that they are unable to propagate effectively through the network:
    • leading to slow or ineffective learning.
  • Non-zero mean: The sigmoid and tanh activation functions have a non-zero mean, which can make it harder for the network to learn the desired mapping between inputs and outputs.
  • Rectified linear units (ReLU): ReLU activation functions have become popular in recent years due to their simplicity, computational efficiency, and improved performance compared to sigmoid and tanh.
    • ReLU activation functions are linear for positive inputs and zero for negative inputs, which results in:
      • fast learning
      • avoids the saturation and vanishing gradient problems.
  • In conclusion, while sigmoid and tanh activation functions were popular in the early days of neural network research, they are no longer widely used due to their limitations. Instead, ReLU activation functions and its variants have become the standard activation functions for deep learning models.
  • Leaky ReLU has non zero derivation for negative values, whether ReLU has zero:
    • model would converge faster than using ReLU
    • could prevent zero gradient problem that talked before
    • all neurons actively participate in estimating the result (predicting)

04. Batch size effect¶

  • A batch in machine learning is a subset of data samples used in one iteration of training.
  • Batching is used in training algorithms to improve computational efficiency and avoid memory overload.
  • It also provides a way to approximate the gradient of the loss function over the entire dataset, which is computationally expensive to calculate directly.
  • The size of the batch determines the trade-off between the accuracy of the gradient approximation and the computational efficiency of the training process.
  • Batch size is an important hyperparameter to consider when training machine learning models, and its choice can impact the performance, speed, and stability of the training process.

Some important points regarding batch size:

  • Batch size trade-off: There is a trade-off between batch size and the quality of the gradient approximation:
    • Larger batch sizes provide a more accurate approximation of the gradient, but also require more memory and computational resources.
  • Batch normalization: It is a technique used in deep learning to normalize the inputs to a layer within each mini-batch, which can help reduce the sensitivity of the model to the batch size.
  • Batch processing and online learning:
    • Batch processing refers to training the model on a batch of data at a time; it is more memory efficient.
    • Online learning refers to updating the model one sample at a time; it can lead to faster convergence.
  • Effect on learning dynamics: The batch size can impact the learning dynamics of the model, such as the convergence rate and stability of the training process.
  • Batch size schedule: In some cases, it may be beneficial to use a batch size schedule, where the batch size is gradually increased or decreased during training:
    • This can help the model converge faster or avoid overfitting.

Using a higher batch size:

  • Advantages:

    1. Speed: Large batches allow the model to process more data in each iteration, which can lead to faster convergence and reduced training time.
    2. Stability: Using large batch sizes can help stabilize the gradient calculation and prevent overfitting in some cases.

  • Disadvantages:

    1. Memory: Larger batches require more memory to store the intermediate results, which can be a limiting factor for training on large datasets or complex models.
    2. Generalization: The larger the batch size, the less diverse the data the model sees in each iteration, which can reduce its ability to generalize to new data.
    3. Over-smoothing: Large batches can result in smoother and less noisy gradients, but this can also lead to over-smoothing and reduce the model's ability to learn fine-grained patterns in the data.

Using a lower batch size:

  • Advantages:

    1. Generalization: Lower batch sizes lead to a more diverse set of samples in each iteration, which can help the model generalize better to new data.
    2. Fine-grained learning: Smaller batches result in noisier and less smooth gradients, which can help the model learn fine-grained patterns in the data that might be missed by a smoother gradient.

  • Disadvantages:

    1. Slow convergence: Smaller batches mean the model updates its parameters less frequently, which can lead to slower convergence and longer training times.
    2. Instability: Lower batch sizes can lead to more unstable gradients, especially in cases where the dataset is highly imbalanced or contains a large number of outliers.
    3. Increased memory requirements: Lower batch sizes result in more updates to the model parameters, which can require more memory to store the intermediate results.

Finding the optimum batch size:

  • It can be an empirical process and is dependent on various factors such as
    1. the size of the dataset
    2. the complexity of the model
    3. the available computational resources (memory and computing power)
  • Power of two rule: Batch size of a power of two (32, 64, 128, etc.) is chosen as it fits well with the memory architecture of most GPUs.
  • Grid search: This involves training the model with different batch sizes and evaluating their performance using a metric such as accuracy or loss.
    • The optimum batch size is then selected based on the performance metric.
  • Learning rate tuning: This involves finding the best learning rate for a fixed batch size, and then adjusting the batch size to achieve the best performance.

Factors that can affect the optimum batch size:

  • Dataset size: A larger dataset requires larger batch sizes to make efficient use of the computational resources.
  • Model complexity: Complex models require smaller batch sizes to prevent overfitting.
  • Computational resources: The amount of memory and computing power available can limit the maximum batch size that can be used.
  • Learning rate: Larger batch sizes can require a lower learning rate to prevent instability.
  • The optimum batch size may not be the same for all datasets and models:
    • it may need to be re-evaluated when changing the model architecture or training dataset.
